I was looking for accent-insensitive test searches and ended up here. And folowing @nursix suggestions, wrote a CustomPostgreSQLAdapter that overwrites the "CONTAINS" operation. It detects if unaccent extension is present and applies it.

Probably not perfect, but let me share, just in case someone else needs it:

```python
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-/
from pydal.adapters import ADAPTERS, PostgreSQLAdapter
from pydal.objects import Expression

class CustomPostgreSQLAdapter(PostgreSQLAdapter):

    installed_extensions = None

    def has_extension(self, name):
        if self.installed_extensions is None:
            installed_extensions = [row[0] for row in self.db.executesql('select extname from pg_extension;')]
        return name in installed_extensions

    def UNACCENT(self, first):
        return 'UNACCENT(%s)' % self.expand(first) if self.has_extension('unaccent') else first

    def CONTAINS(self, first, second, case_sensitive=True):
        if self.has_extension('unaccent') and first.type in ('string', 'text', 'json'):
            first = Expression(first.db, self.UNACCENT, first, None, first.type)
            second = Expression(first.db, self.UNACCENT, self.represent(second, 'string'), None, first.type)
        return super(CustomPostgreSQLAdapter, self).CONTAINS(first, second, case_sensitive)

ADAPTERS.update({
    'custompostgres': CustomPostgreSQLAdapter
})
```

I am not challenging the atomic class.
This appears to be due to the hash table implementation you're using trying to execute an explicit assignment: "__cache->__value_ = *__first;" when inserting the item, where the gcc and msvc implementations uses a copy constructor, which is implemented.

try changing the line:

timing_[shapes][mode] = tm;

to:

timing_[shapes].insert(std::make_pair(mode, tm));

It's a long time know bug (see https://github.com/django-extensions/django-extensions/issues/229 and https://github.com/django-extensions/django-extensions/issues/786).

